\newlabel{fig:class_distribution}{{1a}{10}{Top-level class distribution across 135{,}751 TE sequences in the dataset. Unannotated sequences dominate at 62.3\%. Among annotated classes, LTR (18.8\%), LINE (10.4\%) and DNA (7.9\%) are the principal categories, while minor classes (SINE, PLE, RC) contribute to less than 0.5\%}{figure.caption.3}{}}
\newlabel{sub@fig:class_distribution}{{a}{10}{Top-level class distribution across 135{,}751 TE sequences in the dataset. Unannotated sequences dominate at 62.3\%. Among annotated classes, LTR (18.8\%), LINE (10.4\%) and DNA (7.9\%) are the principal categories, while minor classes (SINE, PLE, RC) contribute to less than 0.5\%}{figure.caption.3}{}}
\newlabel{fig:superfamily_distribution}{{1b}{10}{Superfamily abundances within each top-level class (top 30, excluding None). LTR/Gypsy and LINE/L1 are the most frequent. Within DNA, only seven superfamilies exceed 100 examples; counts span 4{,}900 (DNA/hAT) to 129 (DNA/Maverick). The rare superfamilies present the most demanding classification targets given their limited training support}{figure.caption.3}{}}
\newlabel{sub@fig:superfamily_distribution}{{b}{10}{Superfamily abundances within each top-level class (top 30, excluding None). LTR/Gypsy and LINE/L1 are the most frequent. Within DNA, only seven superfamilies exceed 100 examples; counts span 4{,}900 (DNA/hAT) to 129 (DNA/Maverick). The rare superfamilies present the most demanding classification targets given their limited training support}{figure.caption.3}{}}
